[{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = Backboner\nDocTestSetup = quote\n    using Backboner\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"#Backboner","page":"Home","title":"Backboner","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: Documentation) (Image: Documentation) (Image: Build Status) (Image: Coverage)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This package implements types and functions for working with molecular backbones, defined here as continuous chains of bonded atoms.[1]","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Backbones can be represented with different types:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Backbone: a type containing a 3xN matrix of coordinates\nChainedBonds: a type that holds vectors of bond lengths, bond angles, and torsion angles\nFrames: a collection of rotations and translations (e.g. for representing orientations and locations of protein residues)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Most functions are implemented especially with differentiability in mind, and can be used in combination with automatic differentiation packages like Zygote.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Home","title":"Installation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"using Pkg\npkg\"add Backboner\"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Example-usage","page":"Home","title":"Example usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"julia> using Backboner\n\njulia> backbone = Backbone(rand(Float32, 3, 9))\n10-element Backbone{Float32, Matrix{Float32}}:\n [0.48967552, 0.91008425, 0.5339774]\n [0.2951318, 0.38963223, 0.8952989]\n [0.83763623, 0.5279301, 0.3407849]\n [0.88848716, 0.643387, 0.76827604]\n [0.697279, 0.63588345, 0.0889622]\n [0.08590478, 0.6086006, 0.6478121]\n [0.06308746, 0.6704904, 0.55852276]\n [0.46147835, 0.56259614, 0.7884294]\n [0.9694153, 0.052023113, 0.08127427]\n\njulia> ChainedBonds(backbone)\nChainedBonds{Float32, Vector{Float32}} with 8 bond lengths, 7 bond angles, and 6 torsion angles\n\njulia> is_knotted(backbone)\nfalse","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"[1]: In some contexts, the term backbone may be used more loosely, and allow for atoms that are not part of the main continuous chain of atoms. This package does not support storing e.g. oxygen and beta-carbon atoms in the matrix of coordinates, as they are not part of the continuous chain of atoms.","category":"page"},{"location":"API/#Backboner-API","page":"API","title":"Backboner API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"API/","page":"API","title":"API","text":"Modules = [Backboner]","category":"page"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.Backbone","page":"API","title":"Backboner.Backbone","text":"Backbone{T<:Real,M<:AbstractMatrix{T}} <: AbstractVector{AbstractVector{T}}\n\nThe Backbone type is designed to efficiently store and manipulate the three-dimensional coordinates of backbone points.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.ChainedBonds","page":"API","title":"Backboner.ChainedBonds","text":"ChainedBonds{T<:Real,V<:AbstractVector{T}}\n\nA lazy way to store a backbone as a series of bond lengths, bond angles, and torsion_angles.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> backbone = Backbone(randn(Float32, 3, 660));\n\njulia> bonds = ChainedBonds(backbone)\nChainedBonds{Float32, Vector{Float32}} with 659 bond lengths, 658 bond angles, and 657 torsion angles\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.append_bonds-Tuple{Backbone, AbstractVector{<:Real}, AbstractVector{<:Real}, AbstractVector{<:Real}}","page":"API","title":"Backboner.append_bonds","text":"append_bonds(backbone, bond_lengths, bond_angles, torsion_angles)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.get_displacements-Tuple{Backbone, Integer, Integer, Integer}","page":"API","title":"Backboner.get_displacements","text":"get_displacements(backbone, start, step, stride)\n\nGet the displacements between points in backbone, where start is the index of the first point, step is the offset of the other points along the backbone (e.g. 1 for bond vectors), and stride is the number of points to skip after each step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.get_distances-Tuple{Backbone, Integer, Integer, Integer}","page":"API","title":"Backboner.get_distances","text":"get_distances(backbone, start, step, stride)\n\nGet the Euclidean distances between points in backbone, where start is the index of the first point, step is the offset of the other points along the backbone (e.g. 1 for bond lengths), and stride is the number of points to skip after each step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.is_knotted","page":"API","title":"Backboner.is_knotted","text":"is_knotted(backbone::Backbone)\n\nCheck if a backbone is knotted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"API/#Backboner.prepend_bonds-Tuple{Backbone, AbstractVector{<:Real}, AbstractVector{<:Real}, AbstractVector{<:Real}}","page":"API","title":"Backboner.prepend_bonds","text":"prepend_bonds(backbone, bond_lengths, bond_angles, torsion_angles)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
